Foreword: Data Source

This notebook will be used to assess the correctness of the results and estimation of the GARCH-Family of models. There are some key poits that deserve consideration:

  1. Some estimation showed "convergence problem". Whenever this was the case in the cross-validation process, the model was excluded from the set of models. An example:
    • Given the parameters chosen for $p$, $q$, $o$, $\mu$ and distribution, for each new data-point included in the train data a model was estimated. If the first $x$ models had no problem in convergence, but the $x+1$ model failed to converge, we could obtain a forecast to compute the mean-squared error and thus, the whole model were excluded from the set of models.
  2. To estimate the models, the set of parameters $\left(p, q, o\right)$ is passed to the function. A data frame with the parameters is created, and used to specify the model in later step. This data frame with specification was saved to the database containing the results of each Volatiltiy Model.
  3. There should have been that a data frame containing all the forecasts (for all the models) is saved to the local database. But, as the Kernel kept dying, we could not create this data frame for all the volatility-models. Nevertheless, a part from some data-frames containing the aggregated values, the database also contains tables named:
    • ID_x_model_params: contains the coefficients of the model $x$ for the whole cross-validation and the estimated distribution (when applicable).
    • val_var: The variance-proxy used in the validation (there are three proxies: squared returns, realized volaility, and ajd. realized volatility). The frame contains which target should have been predicted for the $1,\dots, 5$ steps ahead forecasts.
    • ID_x_val_forecast_var: the data frame holds the forecasts made during the cross-validation process using the specifications of model $x$.
    • ID_x_resid_and_cvol: a data frame containing the residua, standardized residua, and conditional volatility for model $x$.
    • ID_x_params_stats: a data frame containing the coefficients of model $x$ as well as t-statistics, confidence intervals and p-values.
    • ID_x_params_conv: a data frame containing the variance covariance matrix of the coefficients.
  4. There is an error in the format of the table containing the aggregated evaluation (named: Agg. Loss Function Values). There is no error in how the evaluation was computed, but in how the data frames were aggregated.
  5. At the end of this notebook we will have created a dataset to hold all the mse computed and all the models specifications.

# ++++ Define function used for cross-validation in the class +++
def CV_RollingFromOrigin(df:pd.DataFrame, min_size:int, h:int):
    """
    A generator to create train and validation split
    for cross validation by using the rolling-forecasting-origin method        
    
    Nota Bene: Make sure that the data set is in ascending order regarding
    the dates.
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    df : pd.DataFrame
        A padas dataframe with the data to be used in the cross-validation.
    min_size : int
        The minimum-size of datapoints needed to estimate the model.
    h : int
        The horizon of the prediction (i.e. the size of the validation set)

    Returns
    -------
    A generator for train and validation splits. The data is returned as a
    one dimensional numpy array.

    """
        
# =============================================================================
# Make sure that the data is passed as a pandas dataframe containing a single
# column, and transform this column to a numpy array.
# =============================================================================
    assert isinstance(df, pd.DataFrame), " ".join([
        'df must be a pandas dataframe.'
        ])
    
    assert df.shape[1] == 1, " ".join(
        ['Data-Frame must contain a single column']
        )
    
    data = df.to_numpy().ravel()
# =============================================================================
# iterate over the data set and make sure to have enough data to create the va-
# lidation set, which is always h-ahead of the train set.
# =============================================================================
    for period in range(len(data) - min_size - h + 1):
# =============================================================================
# The data is added sequentially and the validation split moves with period.
# =============================================================================
        train_split = data[ :min_size + period]
        val_split = data[min_size + period: min_size + period + h]
        
        yield train_split, val_split

def retrieve_tab(engine, tab_name, model_id = None, tab_type = 'agg'):
    
    # +++ create a dictionary to hold the name of the tables in the database +++

    model_id = -1 if tab_type == 'agg' else model_id

    if tab_type != 'agg':

        # +++ assert that an ID is passed in the table is not aggregated +++
        assert model_id != -1, (
            'A model-id must be passed so that a table can be queried from the data-base.'
        )
        
    dict_tables = {'agg': {
        'specification': 'Specification Table',
        'evaluation': 'Agg. Loss Function Values',
        'prediction': 'Agg. Residuals and cond. Volatility',
        'forecasts': 'Agg. Forecasted Variances'
                    },
                   'unique': {
                        'parameters': 'ID_{}_model_params'.format(model_id),
                       'forecasts': 'ID_{}_val_forecast_var'.format(model_id),
                       'variance': 'ID_{}_val_var'.format(model_id),
                       'prediction': 'ID_{}_resid_and_cvol'.format(model_id),
                       'statistics:': 'ID_{}_params_stats'.format(model_id),
                       'covariance': 'ID_{}_params_conv'.format(model_id)
                   }

    }

    # +++ create query to retrieve the data set +++
    query = """
    SELECT *
    FROM "{}"
    """.format(dict_tables[tab_type][tab_name])

    df_queried = pd.read_sql(
        sql = query,
        con = engine
    )

    return df_queried

from arch.univariate import ZeroMean, ARCH, StudentsT

# +++ instantiate the cross-validation generator +++
len_tqdm = len(list(CV_RollingFromOrigin(df = df_return_sp500.index.to_frame(), h = 5, min_size = 250)))
sp500_gen = CV_RollingFromOrigin(df = df_return_sp500.index.to_frame(), h = 5, min_size = 250)

# +++ iterate over the generator +++
counter = 0
for train, val in tqdm(sp500_gen, total = len_tqdm, ncols = 100, desc = 'Cross-Validating Arch-Model (S&P500)'):

    train_data = df_return_sp500.loc[train]
    val_data = df_vol_sp500.loc[val]

    model = ZeroMean(
        train_data,
        volatility = ARCH(p = 30),
        distribution = StudentsT(seed = 19921123)
        
    ).fit(disp = False)

    if counter == 0:

        # +++ get forecasts +++
        df_forecasts_sp500 = model.forecast(horizon = 5, method = 'analytic').variance

        df_validation_adjvar_sp500 = df_forecasts_sp500.copy(deep = True)

        # +++ fill in the df_adj_var_sp500 with the values of the taget variable +++
        df_validation_adjvar_sp500.iloc[0, :] = df_vol_sp500['Adj. Realized Volatility'].loc[val].values

        counter +=1
    else:

        df_forecasts_sp500_temp = model.forecast(horizon = 5, method = 'analytic').variance
        
        df_validation_adjvar_sp500_temp = df_forecasts_sp500_temp.copy(deep = True)
        df_validation_adjvar_sp500_temp.iloc[0, :] = df_vol_sp500['Adj. Realized Volatility'].loc[val].values
        
        df_forecasts_sp500 = pd.concat([df_forecasts_sp500, df_forecasts_sp500_temp], axis = 0)
        
        df_validation_adjvar_sp500 = pd.concat([df_validation_adjvar_sp500, df_validation_adjvar_sp500_temp], axis = 0)

Notice how the data-frame above has 240 'ID_x' for $x = 1, \dots, 240$ columns. These columns were all the indices of separate data-frames; and their values are always 'mse', 'mae', 'mape'. These columns shouldn't exist. Only the metric column (that for now holds integers 0: mse, 1: mae, 2: mape) should contain the names of the loss-functions. There is a single column called 'ID', where the model ID is the same as the ones in the specification dataframe. We will thus drop all the columns that we do not need; we will further map the loss-function name to the 'metric' column and keep only the Mean Squared Error (MSE) in the dataset. In a later step, we keep only the mean squared error in the dataframe, separate the mse- for each volatility proxies in different data-frames, transform the data-frame from wide to long and create a column to assign which volatility proxy was used as target varaible to calculate the mean squared error.

def eval_wide_to_long(df):

    # +++ create a function to map the names of the loss functions +++
    def map_lossname(x):

        x = int(x)
        dict_name = {
            0: 'mse',
            1: 'mae',
            2: 'mape'
        }
    
        return dict_name[x]

    df = df.copy(deep = True)
    # +++ map the name to the loss functions +++
    df["('metric', '')"] = df["('metric', '')"].apply(map_lossname)

    # +++ drop all columns containing an "_", these are the columns in the form ID_x, which we do not need +++
    col_to_keep = [col for col in df.columns if '_' not in col]

    df = df[col_to_keep]
    
    # +++ keep only mse +++
    df = df[df["('metric', '')"] == 'mse']
    
    # +++ obtain the values of the squared return, realized vol and adj realized vol in separate dataframes +++
    col_sq = [col for col in df.columns.tolist() if 'Squared Return' in col] + ["('ID', '')"]

    col_realvol = [col for col in df.columns.tolist() if ('Realized Volatility' in col) and ('Adj.' not in col)] + ["('ID', '')"]

    col_adjrealvol = [col for col in df.columns.tolist() if 'Adj. Realized Volatility' in col] +  ["('ID', '')"]

    df_mse_sq = df[col_sq].copy(deep = True)
    df_mse_realvol = df[col_realvol].copy(deep = True)
    df_mse_adjrealvol = df[col_adjrealvol].copy(deep = True)

    # +++ rename the columns +++
    col_names_sq = ['h.' + ''.join(re.findall(r'\d', column)) if re.findall(r'\d', column) else 'ID' for column in df_mse_sq.columns.tolist()]
    col_names_realvol = ['h.' + ''.join(re.findall(r'\d', column)) if re.findall(r'\d', column) else 'ID' for column in df_mse_realvol.columns.tolist()]
    col_names_adjrealvol = ['h.' + ''.join(re.findall(r'\d', column)) if re.findall(r'\d', column) else 'ID' for column in df_mse_adjrealvol.columns.tolist()]

    # +++ rename the columns of the dataframes +++
    df_mse_sq.columns = col_names_sq
    df_mse_realvol.columns = col_names_realvol
    df_mse_adjrealvol.columns = col_names_adjrealvol


    # +++ create a column in each of the dataframes to hold the volatility proxy +++
    df_mse_sq['Vol Proxy'] = 'Squared Return'
    df_mse_sq.reset_index(drop = True, inplace = True)
    df_mse_realvol['Vol Proxy'] = 'Realized Volatility'
    df_mse_realvol.reset_index(drop = True, inplace = True)
    df_mse_adjrealvol['Vol Proxy'] = 'Adj. Realized Volatility'
    df_mse_adjrealvol.reset_index(drop = True, inplace = True)

    # +++ concat the data frames +++
    df_mse = pd.concat([
        df_mse_sq,
        df_mse_realvol,
        df_mse_adjrealvol
    ], axis = 0)
    return df_mse

1.3. Checking the GARCH Models

We will repeat the process we did in Section 1.2.. These are:

  • Randomly select an ID from the set of estimated models.
  • Check if the parameters meet the model specification.
  • Estimate exactly the same model again, compute MSE and check if they are the same.
  • Each process is done once for the DAX and once for the S&P500.
  • Aggregate the MSE and the specification data-set and save to a database.

We will repeat teh process we did in Section 1.2. for the Egarch models. These are:

  • Randomly select an ID from the set of estimated models
  • Check if the parameters meet the model specification
  • Estimate exactly the same model again, compute MSE and check if they are the same.
  • Each step is done once for the DAX and once for the S&P500.
  • Aggregate the MSE and the specification data-set and save to a database.

1.4.1. Check: Model Parameters

The table containing the model parameters should have an estimate for the mean, the lags $p$ $\left(\alpha_j\right)$, for $j = 1,\dots, 4$, the lags $q$ $\left(\beta_{i}\right)$ and $o$ $\left(\gamma_{i}\right)$ for $i = 1, \dots, 3$, and intercept $\omega$, and the parameters $\eta$ and $\lambda$ that controls the shape and the skewness of the Skew-t distribution.

from arch.univariate import ConstantMean, EGARCH, SkewStudent

len_tqdm = len(list(CV_RollingFromOrigin(df = df_return_sp500.index.to_frame(), h = 5, min_size = 250)))
sp500_gen = CV_RollingFromOrigin(df = df_return_sp500.index.to_frame(), h = 5, min_size = 250)


# +++ iterate over the generator +++
counter = 0
np.random.seed(19921123)

for train, val in tqdm(sp500_gen, total = len_tqdm, ncols = 100, desc = 'Cross-Validating Egarch-Model (S&P500)'):

    train_data = df_return_sp500.loc[train]
    val_data = df_vol_sp500.loc[val]

    model = ConstantMean(
        train_data,
        volatility = EGARCH(p = 4, q = 3, o = 3),
        distribution = SkewStudent(seed = 19921123)
        
    ).fit(disp = False)

    if counter == 0:

        # +++ get forecasts +++
        df_forecasts_sp500 = model.forecast(horizon = 5, method = 'simulation').variance

        df_validation_adjvar_sp500 = df_forecasts_sp500.copy(deep = True)

        # +++ fill in the df_adj_var_sp500 with the values of the taget variable +++
        df_validation_adjvar_sp500.iloc[0, :] = df_vol_sp500['Adj. Realized Volatility'].loc[val].values

        counter +=1
    else:

        df_forecasts_sp500_temp = model.forecast(horizon = 5, method = 'simulation').variance
        
        df_validation_adjvar_sp500_temp = df_forecasts_sp500_temp.copy(deep = True)
        df_validation_adjvar_sp500_temp.iloc[0, :] = df_vol_sp500['Adj. Realized Volatility'].loc[val].values
        
        df_forecasts_sp500 = pd.concat([df_forecasts_sp500, df_forecasts_sp500_temp], axis = 0)
        
        df_validation_adjvar_sp500 = pd.concat([df_validation_adjvar_sp500, df_validation_adjvar_sp500_temp], axis = 0)

Both the tables 1.15 and 1.16 match the model specifications. Hence, we conclude that the parameters were correctly specified.
